content.description:
TAR BABY 5.5 ** 70’ F (8b)

A great little route. Begin at the lowest point of the lower wall about 5’ right of the thin vertical seam, and climb the easy lower face (5.2) through the two roofs (committing crux move at the 2nd roof) to the chain anchors above. This is an enjoyable route with rock that's much better than it looks and climbing that's safe with lots of bolts.
content.protection: Fixed - 8 bolts to chain anchors at the top lip.
content.location: Climbs the middle of the lower face beginning at the lowest point.

content.description:
Side Step 5.3 ** 90' M(5b)

Climbs the shallow corner in the middle of the face, to the side step left at the very top to avoid the overhang below the top anchors (directional anchor at the top lip with the 2 bolt anchors with quick links about 5' to the right)
content.protection: Mixed 5 bolts, several cams and/or nuts (small to large) needed.
content.location: On the wall to the north between the Upper West Side cliff and the SE Buttress, in the middle of the gully, climb the shallow corner in the middle of the face. Begin on the large ledge at the base, reached by a 10' 4th class scramble at the far left end of the short headwall at the base (by the broken pine snag). Belay at the single bolt anchor on the right.

content.description:
MORE GNEISS JUGS… 5.8 ** 65’ F (7b)

Begin as for the other Gneiss route but go up to the right and on to the 2 chain anchors on the upper right top edge.
content.protection: Fixed - 7 bolt to chain anchors on top
content.location: Climbs the right side of the middle of the Upper Face

content.description:
High Step 5.7 ** 80' M(5b)

Begin directly above the bottom single belay anchor bolt and climb the face just right of the shallow corner through a series of ledges to the high step crux at the top. Shares top anchors with Side Step.
content.protection: Mixed, 5 bolts and several small to medium cams.
content.location: Climbs the face just right of the shallow corner in the middle of the face. Begin on the large ledge at the base, reached by a 10' 4th class scramble at the far left end of the short headwall at the base (by the broken pine snag). Belay at the single bolt anchor on the right.

content.description:
HAVE A GNEISS DAY 5.7 *** 55’ F (5b)

A fine short but sustained climb up the middle of the Upper Wall. Begin right of the large ground level roof and traverse left to gain the highly featured face. 2 ring anchors on top.
content.protection: Fixed - 5 bolts, ring anchors on top
content.location: The left route up the middle of the Upper Face

content.description:
COYOTE AND ROADRUNNER 5.7 ** 70’ F (6b)

Begin about 50' up and right of the Tar Baby face at the base of the arete with the small crumbling overhang at the bottom. Climb through the overhang (crux) which is better than it looks, and follow the arete on excellent rock to the 2 chain anchors on top.
content.protection: fixed - 6 bolts + 2 chain anchors (several medium small cam placements are possible between some of the bolts).
content.location: About 50' up and right of the start of Br'er Rabbit in the lower gully.

content.description:
BR’ER RABBIT 5.4 ** 70’ F (6b)

Begin about 5’ right of “Tar Baby” and climb diagonally right (5.2 to the first bolt). Continue up through the right side of the middle roof (may want to place a small cam here). This is an easier but bolder route than its neighbor on rock that is generally better than it looks. Shares the top 10’ and chain anchors with “Tar Baby.”
content.protection: Fixed - 6 bolts (shares top bolt and anchors with Tar Baby, and a #.5 cam placement is possible in the middle of the upper crux section.
content.location: Starts 5' right of Tar Baby at the base of the lower face.
